"Beaugrand G., Kirby R.R.","Spatial changes in the sensitivity of Atlantic cod to climate-driven effects in the plankton",2010,"Climate Research","41","1",,"15","19",,,10.3354/cr00838,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953376579&partnerID=40&md5=e702376beea6b6ae7ad37244f498036d","Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (CNRS), Laboratoire D'Océanologie et de Géosciences, UMR LOG CNRS 8187, Université des Sciences et Technologies Lille, 1, BP 80, 62930 Wimereux, France; Sir Alister Hardy Foundation for Ocean Science, The Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth PL12PB, United Kingdom; School of Marine Science and Engineering, University of Plymouth, Drake Circus, Plymouth PL4 8AA, United Kingdom","Beaugrand, G., Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (CNRS), Laboratoire D'Océanologie et de Géosciences, UMR LOG CNRS 8187, Université des Sciences et Technologies Lille, 1, BP 80, 62930 Wimereux, France, Sir Alister Hardy Foundation for Ocean Science, The Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth PL12PB, United Kingdom; Kirby, R.R., Sir Alister Hardy Foundation for Ocean Science, The Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth PL12PB, United Kingdom, School of Marine Science and Engineering, University of Plymouth, Drake Circus, Plymouth PL4 8AA, United Kingdom","Recent strategies to sustain fish stocks have suggested a move towards an ecosystem based fisheries management (EBFM) approach. While EBFM considers the effect of fishing at the ecosystem level, it generally struggles with climate-driven environmental variability. In this study we show that the position of a fish stock within its distributional range or thermal niche (we use Icelandic and North Sea cod as examples of stocks at the centre and edge of their niche, respectively) will influence the relative importance of fishing and climate on abundance. At the warmer edge of the thermal niche of cod in the North Sea, we show a prominent influence of climate on the cod stock that is mediated through temperature effects on the plankton. In contrast, the influence of climate through its effects on plankton appears much less important at the present centre of the niche around Iceland. Recognising the potentially strong effect of climate on fish stocks, at a time of rapid global climate change, is probably an important prerequisite towards the synthesis of a cod management strategy. © Inter-Research 2010.","Climate change; Cod; Fishing; Plankton; Temperature","Climate-driven effects; Cod; Ecosystem levels; Environmental variability; Fish stock; Fisheries management; Global climate changes; Icelandics; Icelands; Management strategies; North Sea; Relative importance; Spatial changes; Temperature effects; Ecology; Fisheries; Ocean habitats; Climate change; climate change; climate effect; fishing; gadoid; niche; plankton; range size; spatial variation; stock assessment; temperature effect; Atlantic Ocean; Iceland; North Sea; Gadus morhua",,,,,,"Beaugrand, G., Kirby, R.K., Climate, plankton and cod (2009) Glob Change Biol., , press doi:10.1111/j.1365-2486.2009. 02063.x; Beaugrand, G., Brander, K.M., Lindley, J.A., Souisi, S., Reid, P.C., Plankton effect on cod recruitment in the North Sea (2003) Nature, 426, pp. 661-664; Beaugrand, G., Edwards, M., Brander, K., Luczak, C., Ibañez, F., Causes and projections of abrupt climate-driven ecosystem shifts in the North Atlantic (2008) Ecol. Lett., 11, pp. 1157-1168; Brander, K., ICES/GLOBEC cod and climate change programme: Results and achievements (2003) GLOBEC Int. News, 9, pp. 20-22; Brander, K.M., Global fish production and climate change (2007) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 104, pp. 19709-19714; Frank, K.T., Petrie, B., Choi, J.S., Leggett, W.C., Trophic cascades in a formerly cod-dominated ecosystem (2005) Science, 308, pp. 1621-1623; (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis, , IPCC Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Jackson, J.B.C., Ecological extinction and evolution in the brave new ocean (2008) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 105, pp. 11458-11465; Kirby, R.R., Beaugrand, G., Lindley, J., Synergistic effects of climate and fishing in a marine ecosystem (2009) Ecosystems, 12, pp. 548-561; Lomolino, M.V., Riddle, B.R., Brown, J.H., (2006) Biogeography. Sinauer Associates, , New York; Myers, R.A., Hutchings, J.A., Barrowman, N.J., Hypothesis for the decline of cod in the north Atlantic (1996) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 138, pp. 293-308; Pikitch, E.K., Santora, C., Babcock, E.A., Bakun, A., Ecosystem-based fishery management (2004) Science, 305, pp. 346-347. , others; Planque, B., Fredou, T., Temperature and the recruitment of Atlantic cod (Gadus morhua) (1999) Can. J. Fish Aquat Sci., 56, pp. 2069-2077; Platt, T., Fuentes-Yaco, C., Frank, K.T., Spring algal bloom and larval fish survival (2003) Nature, 423, pp. 398-399; Pyper, B.J., Peterman, R.M., Comparison of methods to account for autocorrelation analyses of fish data (1998) Can. J. Fish Aquat Sci., 55, pp. 2127-2140; Reid, P.C., Colebrook, J.M., Matthews, J.B.L., Aiken, J., The continuous plankton recorder: Concepts and history, from plankton indicators to undulating recorders (2003) Prog. Oceanogr, 58, pp. 117-173; Rothschild, B.J., Shannon, L.J., Regime shifts and fishery management (2004) Prog. Oceanogr, 60, pp. 397-402; Sundby, S., Recruitment of Atlantic cod stocks in relation to temperature and advection of copepod populations (2000) Sarsia, 85, pp. 277-298","Beaugrand, G.; Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (CNRS), Laboratoire D'Océanologie et de Géosciences, UMR LOG CNRS 8187, Université des Sciences et Technologies Lille, 1, BP 80, 62930 Wimereux, France; email: gregory.beaugrand@univ-lille1.fr",,,,,,,,0936577X,,,,"English","Clim. Res.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-77953376579
